From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
< Wikipedia:WikiProject Quality Article Improvement

This list shows the recipients of Precious, a prize of WP:QAI for precious support. Example:

"grant each other the presumption that we are acting in good faith"

Thank you for handling images, including your helpful bot dealing with non-free images, for {{Virginia Tech Hokies bowl game navbox}} and imagining rising, for addressing users in welcome and warning, for brevity in username, statement and comment, for putting man-made constructs into perspective and "grant each other the presumption that we are acting in good faith", - you are an awesome Wikipedian!

The history, dating back to 2007, was archived on 1 July 2022 to Wikipedia:WikiProject Quality Article Improvement/Precious archive. Reminders of the award are sent annually to users who were active during the last year, until the tenth year, when a special award is given as a final reminder. Everybody is welcome to award a user who is not yet on the list. --Gerda Arendt (talk) 10:45, 14 November 2022 (UTC)[reply]

Before (2012–2024)[edit]

The following table is originally sorted by date. For each recipient, it has the most recent user name (linked to the award) in the first column, then day and month of the award (sortable for that), the year (sortable by date), the summary title given with the award, the historic assigned Precious number, the number of a ten-years reminder (linked to it), and comments. The historic table was updated. --Gerda Arendt (talk) 11:52, 13 November 2022 (UTC)[reply]

A new feature in the notes indicates if a user is a member of W:QAI (), and if a user was active during the last year (Y), meaning more than around 10 edits to articles. --Gerda Arendt (talk) 07:57, 31 December 2022 (UTC)[reply]

Most awards were given by me, but several others helped, also marked in the notes. You can help! Other features there include that a user died (+), or refused the award (- d = decline) or reminders (- u = unsubscribe). The icon - is given for others alive but certainly not active (vanished, banned, retired). --Gerda Arendt (talk) 08:57, 4 January 2023 (UTC)[reply]
